This project creates hotspot maps in the City of Fairfax for larceny calls from 2007 to April 30, 2023.

Hotspots Per Day for Larceny Calls

## generated.

This graph shows the hotspots for crimes based on the day of week that they occurred. The hotspots and coldspots throughout each day of the week remain very consistent with one another. However, these common hotspot locations experience more larcenies on Tuesday, Friday, Sunday, and Wednesday with the largest hotspot occurring around 236, 123, and North Street where there is a large cluster of businesses. In the future these hotspots will most likely remain the same as they are around popular locations within the City of Fairfax that are unlikely to become unpopular in the near future. In addition, these hotspots will remain the same in the future because they are consistent throughout all days of the week so it can be assumed that this pattern will continue.

Hotspots Per Hour for Larceny Calls

The hotspots throughout the various hours of the day remain very consistent with slight changes. However, one major inconsistency is the hotspot that occurs in the East of the City of Fairfax around Pickett Road to Blenheim Boulevard. This inconsistent hotspot only occurs for the hours 11, 12, 14 to 17, and 19 to 21. In general,there is a major hotspot around 236, 123, and North Street throughout all hours of the day. Coldspots for larcenies are at their highest during the hours 3 to 8, 22, and 23. The hotspots that will most likely remain the same in the future is the spot occurring around Pickett Road, 236, and 123 because it occurs at all hours of the day, so it can be expected that if no significant changes are made to the area it will continue to be a hotspot.

Hotspots Per Month for Larceny Calls

The hotspots remain very consistent across every month with the largest hotspot occurring around Pickett Road, 236, and 123. March has the least number of hotspots and the smallest hotspots in comparison to the other months hotspots. A hotspot around 29 and Blenheim Boulevard occurs in every month, but is largest in September and January. The coldspots shift slightly throughout the year, but one location that is consistently cold is in the North on the West side of the City of Fairfax where there are more residences than businesses. This cold spot will most likely continue as it occurs in every graph made through out this project making it a constant cold spot. The consistent hotspot around Pickett Road will continue to exist in the future with slight variations in the size, as it occurred in every month in this graph and was a constant in the graphs in this project.
